ollar corporation","body":"In 1901 he merged Carnegie Steel with smaller producers to form U.S. Steel, capitalized at $1.4 billion when the entire federal budget was under $500 million. Andrew Carnegie reportedly named his price on a slip of paper, and Morgan replied 'I accept' without negotiation."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Disfiguring rhinophyma made him hate cameras","body":"A skin condition called rhinophyma transformed his nose into a bulbous purple mass in middle age. He refused most photographs and detested social engagements; the few portraits that exist were heavily retouched on his orders."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Built one of the world's greatest art collections","body":"He spent decades and a fortune assembling Renaissance manuscripts, Old Masters paintings, and ancient artifacts; at his death in 1913 his collection was valued near $50 million. Half of it was donated to the Metropolitan Museum of Art by his son and remains core to the Met today."},{"number":5,"category":"death","header":"Pujo Committee testimony broke his health","body":"In December 1912 he was forced to testify before the Pujo Committee investigating his 'money trust'; the Senate hearings exhausted him and he sailed for Europe to recover. He died in Rome on March 31, 1913, three months after taking the stand."}],"slug":"john-morgan-1837"},"X00360":{"id":"X00360","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1845},"death":{"year":1924},"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD1170","date_year":1865,"date_month":5,"date_day":31,"children_ids":["HD1171","HD1172","HD1173","HD1174"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bi